How to lower cortisol levels

Peta Bee
Wednesday March 09 2022, 5.00pm GMT, The Times

1. Doodle or draw every day

Cortisol is a hormone produced by the adrenal glands and released into the bloodstream when the body undergoes stress. In healthy individuals cortisol levels are highest in the morning and gradually drop throughout the day to a low in the evening so that healthy sleeping patterns are maintained. However, too much stress can lead to chronically higher levels that are associated with greater body weight, BMI and waist circumference. A study in the journal Neurology has also shown that raised cortisol can be linked to poorer memory and thinking skills.

Blood, saliva and hair tests are available to keep an eye on cortisol, but combating it with creativity is an effective first step. German researchers invited a group of 39 adults, half of whom had no experience in making art, to participate in 45 minutes of creativity and provided them with markers and paper, modelling clay and collage materials. Even doodling worked and results showed that 75 per cent of the participantsâ cortisol levels lowered during the art session with no correlation between past art experiences and lower levels.

2. Take a 20-minute ânature pillââ

Something as simple as spending 20 minutes outside every day can help to counter rising cortisol, scientists at the University of Michigan have reported. Over eight weeks, the researchers asked participants to take a daily ânature pillââ by spending at least ten minutes outside three times a week while they kept tabs on levels.

The study leader MaryCarol Hunter, an associate professor in ecology, allowed participants to choose the time of day, duration and place of their nature experience, with the only constraints being that it must be in daylight, entail no vigorous aerobic exercise, and that people should not use their phones or read during the period.

Her results showed that sitting or walking in nature for 20 minutes was enough to significantly reduce levels, but that immersing yourself in nature for 30 minutes produced the greatest rate of decline in the stress hormone.

3. Phone a friend

Good friends are among the best antidotes to rising levels. Last year, a study in the Journal of Women & Ageing showed that for women of all ages communicating with close friends decreased cortisol. âFamiliar partners and friendship buffer stress, and thatâs preserved with age,â says Dr Michelle Rodrigues, a psychologist who led research at the University of Illinois.

Part of the reason is that you are more likely to smile and laugh, which leaves people better equipped to deal with stress, reported a team from the University of Basel. Even the anticipation of humorous laughter with a friend has the power to reduce potentially detrimental stress hormones including cortisol.
